description: 1111 Lighthouse Ave, Pacific Grove, CA 93940. In a park.
no dark stripe below the white stripe on side, light colored stripes on face, white cheeks, fairly bushy tail and right location/habitat for a Panamint Chipmunk

Very close to the Nevada state line and in country I was not familiar with. 
I originally thought Uinita but the populations in California are so limited and scattered that I hesitated to give that ID. However, I looked at pictures of and sightings on inaturalist. 
I believe my original thought was correct. It is a very brown chipmunk with some orange on the side. Bi color ears with a white spot behind the ear. The lower dark stripe is indistinct. Facial stripes are prominent and dark, cheeks white. 
The kicker for me is the tail. It has a very grizzled appearance.I found several examples on inaturalist of this species with very similar looking tails. This is not something I have personally seen in other Chipmunks where I live. 
If I am wrong, feel free to offer a differing opinion.

Eastern slope of the Sierras. No dark stripe below the white stripe on side. Grayish head, dark stripe below the eye fades as it goes around the ear, large white spot behind the ears, some orange on the front of the ear. 
I am confident this was a Panamint Chipmunk.

Wildfire in grove of Foxtail Pine, near Bullfrog Lake, Kings Canyon National Park, CA. Continuous ground fuel was sparse -- mostly dirt and gravel. Fire spread by crowning and sparks to next clump of fuel below live trees. Probably started by camper burning toilet paper.

These pretty much dominate the floating docks at the Berkeley Marina, as far as I could tell. And by dominate I mean coat. Apparently they were introduced from the North Atlantic. Between Pacific Tides claims they require "relatively clean water." Does that mean Berkeley Marina is relatively clean? Seems doubtful...

description: Went down to the Berkeley Marina to investigate fouling communities.  Many tunicates I have yet to ID, but I did find this familiar friend.

These were some of the few visible animals out there.  It's sort of the dead time of year, similar to the dead of winter back East, when not a lot is stirring.  But the Fence Lizards are out in force, mostly tiny little hatchlings, but adults too.
Along the Embarcadero, sleeping on some of the pylons.
Saw a pair walking along the sidewalk on Hillegasse.  Again, acting human.  Creepy.

People have been reporting sightings of a LIttle Blue Heron along Alameda Creek for the past week, so Sarah and I decided to go look for it.  After biking east from the Isherwood staging area, we finally spooked it near the Old Canyon Road overpass.  I've seen them back east, but this was my first one in the west.  Very Pretty bird.
